30 Existing law: (1) establishes criminal liability relating to abuse or neglect of a
31 child under certain circumstances by prohibiting a person who is responsible for the
32 safety or welfare of a child from permitting or allowing the child to be placed in a
33 situation where the child may suffer unjustifiable physical pain or mental suffering
34 as the result of abuse or neglect; and (2) provides that such a person does not
35 commit such abuse or neglect solely because the person delivers or allows the
36 delivery of a child to a provider of emergency services. (NRS 200.508) Section 4
37 of this bill similarly provides that a person who is responsible for the safety or
38 welfare of a child does not commit abuse or neglect of a child solely because the
39 person: (1) seeks to have the child admitted into a public or private mental health
40 facility or hospital if the behavioral health needs of the child pose a risk to the
41 safety and welfare of the family; or (2) brings into the home of the child a
42 biological, foster or adoptive child whose behavioral health needs pose a risk to the
43 safety and welfare of the family. Section 3 of this bill makes a conforming change
44 to refer to provisions that have been renumbered by section 4.
